  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Share evidence and legal resources across borders\n- Extradition agreements for financial criminals\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Shared compliance protocols for financial institutions\n- Efforts to create uniform global regulatory frameworks\n\n4. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- International financial intelligence networks\n- Cross-border reporting systems\n- Collaborative databases tracking suspicious financial transactions\n\n5. Compliance Enforcement\n- International sanctions for non-compliance\n- Pressure on countries to implement robust AML frameworks\n- Economic consequences for inadequate regulatory systems\n\n6. Legal Precedents\n- International court decisions\n- Transnational legal interpretations\n- Development of common legal principles\n\nThese intersections create complex, multilayered approaches to combating money laundering globally.",
